# TodoEditor syncText is 150 ms debounced — tests must flush

`TodoEditorRepresentable.Coordinator.syncText(editedRange:)` (around line 6161) defers the `textBinding.wrappedValue = serialized` write by 150 ms via a `DispatchWorkItem`. `styleTodoParagraphs()` runs synchronously above for visual correctness, but the binding write is coalesced so the full-document `serialize()` doesn't run on every keystroke.

This design is correct for production — it keeps O(n) attribute enumeration off the keystroke path — but it means any unit test that:

1. Pumps the run loop for less than 150 ms
2. Reads the text binding after a block insert or character insert

...will see stale (or empty) binding state. The storage itself is mutated correctly; it's just not serialized back to the binding yet.

**Why:** April 2026 four editor regression tests (`testCommandMenuDividerInsert…`, `testCommandMenuTableInsert…`, `testFirstCharacterOnEmptyNoteStaysOnFirstLine`, `testTabsInsertAfterCallout…`) broke when the debounce was added in commit `91c0dd8`. The 50 ms test pump returns 100 ms before the debounced work item fires.

**How to apply:** The Coordinator exposes `flushPendingSerialization()` specifically for tests. It cancels the pending work item and runs `serialize()` synchronously. The test harness's `pumpMainLoop(_ harness:)` helper in `JotTests/TodoEditorInsertRegressionTests.swift` already calls it — any new editor test should use that helper instead of raw `RunLoop.main.run(until:)`. Do NOT make the debounce conditional on `#if TEST` or lengthen the pump interval; the flush hook is the correct seam and leaves production behavior untouched.
